##Diamond Princess Evacuation: One in five passengers confirmed as new crown, crew continues quarantine

Wechat, chinanewsweekly

Function introduction, here is "China News weekly" the head of the weekly gentleman, the influence has the influence you. Come with me to break through the fog, to find the truth, to watch the Times.

"floating prison. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The "Diamond Princess" from Bermuda, a huge luxury cruise ship

At 7.30 pm on February 18th a broadcast was broadcast from the diamond princess, reminding passengers to note a letter on the door of their rooms. Passengers must quickly open the door, pick up the letter, and then close it. They were not allowed to leave the room except for a two-day walk-out. This has been going on for 14 days, and it's finally coming to an end. In the letter, the Deputy Minister of the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare informed him of plans and plans to disembark the following day (19 February) after the quarantine period had expired.

Less than a month after a new coronavirus infected a passenger aboard the diamond princess on Jan. 20, the ship became the focus of the outbreak outside mainland China. So far, the ship has been subjected to PCR testing of 2,404 people, the total number of infected people reached 542. That means one out of every five people on this ship is infected. In order to prevent the spread of the disease from the waters to the mainland, the Japanese government required the waters around Yokohama to be isolated from the coast for two weeks before it could land. The original "Diamond Princess" was therefore known as the "floating prison.

The radio continued to ring, asking passengers to follow the instructions in the letter on Feb. 19 and to take their belongings with them. Once they had disembarked, they were no longer allowed to return. During the day of February 18th, a doctor had patrolled the room and asked the passengers about their health. Each passenger was presented with a health check card that counted their personal information, past medical history, symptoms of respiratory infections such as fever or headache, runny nose and sore throat, and history of close contact with the infected person, and whether or not a PCR test was performed, and based on these indicators, the doctor made a decision as to whether the passenger was fit to disembark.

At noon on the 18th, the passengers had lunch delivered by the crew, including beef rice and fried rice with eggs. Knowing that the evacuation would begin tomorrow, many of the passengers could not wait to return home as soon as possible and taste the food at home.

Prepare and disembark

On February 18th Katsunobu Kato, a Japanese Minister of Health, Labour and Welfare, said that all the samples taken by the crew of the diamond princess to test for new pneumonia had been collected. Passengers who tested negative for the new coronavirus nucleic acid and had no close contact with the infected person, and who disembarked without any fever and inhalation-related symptoms, may be evacuated from the ship from February 19 to February 21.

The Japanese government has been stepping up testing for two days on the 17th and 18th, but the results of the newly collected samples will not be available for another two days at the earliest, and the evacuation will take three days to wait for the results. If the passengers and crew test positive, will be sent to the local Japanese hospital for treatment.

Embassies around the world are stepping up efforts to reach out to their passengers. On 15 February, the governments of Canada and Italy decided to send charter flights to evacuate their citizens. On February 17th the governments of South Korea and the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China also confirmed their plans to evacuate overseas Chinese by chartered flights.

Of the 311 Chinese passengers on board, 260 were Hong Kong citizens. A 20-strong advance team comprising officers from the Security Bureau, the Immigration Department and the Department of Health was Security Bureau on the 17th. On February 18, an additional eight-person medical team was dispatched.

On February 19, the first day of the evacuation, a total of 500 people were allowed to leave the diamond princess. According to the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, most of the passengers were elderly people who took buses to bus stops and then from bus stops to Yokohama and other stops. According to John Lee, the head of the Security Bureau, at least 20 of the 500 first arrivals were from Hong Kong. Earlier, on Feb. 14, people over 80 had been allowed off the ship.

At 9:45 a.m. on Feb. 19, the ship's broadcast informed passengers that planes from the Hong Kong and Australian governments would arrive in Yokohama within 24 hours. A plane from the Canadian government will not arrive until Friday morning. Some of the passengers were happy, some were anxious. They stare at their cell phones and keep an eye on embassy announcements.

The bus had reached the port of Yokohama and looked out of the cabin window. Two rows of Red Barricades and police cordons formed a long corridor across the harbor.

Passengers on the diamond princess were given colour-coded baggage tags to identify the lot they were disembarking from. At 10 a.m. , passengers with blue luggage tags bearing the number 2 were first notified to assemble at the Gangway on Deck 4, where they were given a health card to wait for their temperature to be taken, it lists a phone number to contact if symptoms develop and a landing permit issued by the Japanese government.

At 11 a.m. , when the first bus left the dock, two passengers left on foot, surrounded by reporters.

According to the Diamond Princess's Feb. 18 announcement, the crew will most likely remain on board for continued isolation of the same standard as the passengers after all passengers have been evacuated.

Previously, the diamond Princess's crew had been quarantined in cramped communal quarters and dined in communal dining rooms. When the quarantine plan was first announced, the Japanese government decided that passengers were more susceptible to infection because of their age and health, so it only imposed higher quarantine standards on passengers. With the rapid increase in the number of people infected, especially the large number of asymptomatic infections, this decision exposed problems. The diamond princess has now announced that the crew will be compensated for the decision to continue quarantining and will be given two months'paid leave at the end of the quarantine.

Because some countries have announced that they will send special planes to pick up their citizens on board the cruise ship, some eligible people on board may not be able to leave immediately and will stay on the cruise ship until the relevant flights arrive.

Those passengers whose roommates tested positive would have to recalculate the new quarantine period from the day they were moved, and then have a new coronavirus test. Disembarkation will not be allowed until the new quarantine period has expired and the test results are negative.

Once the quarantine is complete, the diamond princess will be transported to a private dock, where it will be strictly sterile at the operating room level.

The continuing panic and isolation

On February 16, Huang Yaxi, a Hong Kong tourist, was dismayed to learn that he would be subjected to a 14-day quarantine on his return to Hong Kong. She tweeted pictures of the quarantine room, complaining that it was almost as small as the one on the ship. Huang worries that the continued isolation will cause psychological pressure on the family's elderly and her 6-year-old son.

For the past 14 days, there has been panic on the ship because of a lack of staff testing or a shortage of essential drugs. With the end of the quarantine, some of the panic has abated, but some fears remain. Huang Yaxi told China News weekly that she knew that there were many couples and friends on the ship who were diagnosed at different times, because there were not enough beds and arrangements could not be made for the same hospital, that is the biggest concern for many of those who remain in Japan for treatment. Previously, there was an old man on the diamond princess who was traveling with seven friends, all of whom were over 70 years old and had been given a nucleic acid test. The old man, who was 69 years old at the time, had not yet been tested, he feared that if his friend tested positive and went to another hospital, he would lose contact with them.

Another concern is the large number of asymptomatic infections. Of the 88 confirmed cases, 65 had no symptoms of fever or cough. This poses a challenge to the protection work of governments when organizing centralized evacuation.

The United States government gave American passengers the option of completing the 14-day quarantine on board the ship as originally planned, continuing to isolate themselves in Japan for 14 days after disembarkation and not returning to the United States until March 4. The other is to follow the United States government on February 16 sent two planes back to the United States ahead of schedule, in the mainland to resume the 14-day mandatory quarantine period.

Most American citizens chose to follow the plane back, but some chose to stay on the ship. US Passenger Matthew Smith said it was unreasonable to charter a plane back to the United States for passengers who had not been quarantined for 14 days and had not been tested for coronavirus. While some American passengers were on their way to the airport to return to the United States, tests came back from Japan, and 14 Americans who were about to board the plane tested positive for the new coronavirus. The patients eventually got on the plane with the others. The evacuation of the United States government has also been widely questioned and criticized.

The Hong Kong government has opted for a more stringent quarantine policy. All passengers, whether they choose to return to Hong Kong directly on government flights or after a stay outside Hong Kong, will be placed in quarantine centres for 14 days upon arrival. Earlier, the Hong Kong government temporarily converted a low-cost apartment for low-income people into an isolation point because the four existing isolation points were full, and 269 beds were set aside for passengers disembarking from the diamond princess.

The "floating prison" of the diamond princess is slowly being emptied, but once everyone is on land, a new round of fate awaits.
